Hello it's the anon who tags. I will return back to tagging in 2 weeks at the most. When I figure out how to remove my name from the .git file Ill try to post something to github. Here is what I have or will complete with my work so far:

To help me tag better and faster:
> Tagging workflow: hyperlinks allow me to click a link in my catalogue text file on my computer to take me to the corresponding text file of the paste on my computer.
>Opening fic text files automatically opens my notes
>developing syntax/regexp standards for the catalogue to account for human error when typing things to catalogue txt
>1-2 length keystroke commands allow me to go to the exact line of interest from an output from a program that analyzes my catalogue txt file.
>...alot of other stuff...
To make a better tagging catalogue:
>tagging thesaurus to get rid of or increase redundancy
>https request that allow me to know the date created, edited, etc. and let me put those values in the library. Takes me 20 minutes to get this information for every paste in the library (does not include time for html parsing and data storing). Any faster an pastebin.com will ban my IP.
>regexp sequences that allow me to transfer my weird cryptic tagging symbols and operators to something that everyone can under stand

My goal is to make a dynamic tagging system and workflow b/c 4chan and its non central way of doing things. I also want to tag in a way that is closest to what the author would agree with (as hard as that sounds), which means Conservative and objective leaning tagging. However, there are some relatively more subjective tags such as comfy. So far, if the author says its comfy then the tag comfy will be there, the rest that are tagged comfy are just me saying this story would most likely be relatively less emotionally stressful or triggering(lol) than the other stories if its not already obviously comfy. (just thinking about the grey area of the comfy tag is stressing me out, lol)

Hey everyone, JacklinMauer here. I have something for you. I figured that a good way to kick off the first day of October would be to post the first six chapters of my new story:

The Cracked Pearl
https://pastebin.com/QFW3rU3t
>"I don't care what they call him now. I don't care what some stuffy scholar or some wild zealot says decades after the fact. His 'redemption' means nothing to me or to the tens of thousands he butchered. I was there. I saw him. He was no "Messenger", he was a cannibal. And I will never forgive him". -Jertson, veteran in the Battle of the Northern Bergonite fields.

I will be releasing this in chunks from here on out. I simply don't have the time or resources to push everything out all at once at a reasonable time. My writing projects have gotten bigger and I have less time. For example these six chapters total 22,724 words. I haven't even scratched the surface. I'm not even remotely close to any sort of set goal. I'm going to say that this will total 160k words. Oh boy.

This is the first time I am writing fantasy. This is also the first time I'm using green text combined with a traditional third person narrative. It's been difficult to adjust. My biggest goal for these six chapters is that it is
A.) Fun to read
B.) Easy to understand what's going on.
Please let me know if I succeed. Perfect writing isn't the goal (It should never be the goal) but to make sure that you, the reader, understand what's going on in a way that keeps you invested and interested. If I do that with this initial set of chapters I will have done my job properly. This is basically the first draft of a novel I want to get published at some point. So nailing these early parts will help me tremendously. Typos and grammar errors are pretty standard for me at this point. I can never catch all of them, I don't think it'll be too bad this time around though.
I will be getting another set of chapters out at a later time. You will have another update before the year is out.

Right away, as I was reading, I stopped when I started reading a massive wall of exposition. Don't do that. Drop your character (and reader) directly into the thick of the narrative. You will kill 99% of your readership when you start with exposition. Start off with the main character and perpsective of the scene doing something. Just do anything other than try to give us backstory for characters we don't care about.

Line 22 and then line 30 are tense jumps, but not enough is done in between them to prepare the reader. Your tense jumps a lot, so I'd just be mindful of that.

>The Patriarch turns around, obviously not happy at the possibility of something ELSE to distract him.
Try to avoid emotional tells if you can, but I'm not licensed to give much advice on this since I do it too

">This family in question were distant cousins to the Oakenhowlers, at least that what was being claimed by this servant.
>The Husband had been a trader. Him and his wife had been lost at sea along with most of their merchandise.
>Leaving their only child, a son, with virtually nothing.
>The servant scraped up what money was left and brought the child to a small town not far from the Oakenhowler residence, hoping that the Patriarch would take the boy in."
- This whole bit of exposition should actually be dialogue.

>exclaimed angrily as he eyed the letter
Most editors will tell you to avoid adverbs like -ly. Demonstrate his anger. You can get away with it in a few instances

>“Yes Vugo!” The boy said as he quickly ran back to the old mouse’s side. A furred paw nestles comfortably around the child’s shoulder.
This is kind of what I mean with the tense jumps. You have past tense with 'The boy SAID' and then you have 'paw nestles'

So this is coming from someone who writes greentext stories, but here's something I caught that's unique to greens

>Then Andi saw the large Oak fortress of the Oakenhowler estates.
>And he finally looked like a child again.

The first line should actually be void of its period, becuase these are two connecting thoughts that are seperated. The second line should be the only one that has the period.

>Even at his young age, he could tell the boy was a runt. Small with a skinny frame; an unfortunate combination.
The expression 'a runt' already implies this. We don't necessarily need to know what that looks like on Andi.

>His blonde locks of hair probably hadn’t been cut since before his parents perished at sea. His hair was naturally wavy but when long enough would curl at the tips.
Turn this into dialogue. Have the grouchy Steward say something like "look at the boy, he looks like a yellow wolven (or whatever you're calling them). When was the last time you had this boy groomed proper?"

>With a flick of his finger the child’s awkward introduction was accepted.
Show this with action and dialogue. Follow this up with some dialogue.

>“I hope you understand why I didn’t mention this in my letter” Vugo says.
I notice you forget to add some punctuation here at the end of letter. Should be a comma.

Alright, I read the first chapter. I think you've got a good start, but some mechanical things that are holding this back from really shining.
